g an exception here could go against the intended behavior of the library.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Mockito with Scala objects**\\n\\nI’m trying to understand how to keep coverage interface-based since proxies only support interfaces. Yet, I’m realizing that active call sites for object mocking can't be interface-based. I wonder if using a Scala object that extends a trait could help. I might need a ClassTag for the singleton type. \\n\\nCould I define something like `object Foo extends Interface` to make the mock maker recognize the real class? However, it seems tricky since the object type might not essentially fit the requirements for mocking. Maybe `withObjectSpied` could work if it extends a Java or Scala interface?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Proxy Maker functionality**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the proxy maker validates that the type is an interface. I wonder if `MockSettingsImpl.build(realClass)` could involve a concrete object while considering any extra interfaces. It’s tricky since the default inline maker in the JVM might use resource proxies that affect both the native environment and tests. \\n\\nWhen using `withObjectMocked`, it seems to fail because of these proxy limitations. I realize we don’t have to run the tests ourselves, but it’s essential to produce compiling tests that pass externally.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_4keCRw0OumF9bIqolJw2ZaYu|fc_0d3d9b07ae1a1621016a28db68e38881978bbf4a2ca1fb4975", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-scala_2.13/2.0.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json", "limit": 200}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-scala_2.13/2.0.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json\",\"limit\":200}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1972, "output": 936, "cacheRead": 22528, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 25436, "cost": {"i